<TITLE> European shares sag as credit fears resurface </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, Aug 28 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - European shares snapped a seven-day rally on Tuesday as concern resurfaced about the impact of tight liquidity and high volatility on the corporate sector. The FTSEurofirst 300 index of top European shares unofficially ended down 1.8 percent at 1,488.92 points, having erased almost all of this year's gains, but still about 4 percent higher than the eight-month lows struck on Aug. 17. Bank shares led the index lower for most of the day, with BNP Paribas shedding 3.4 percent, Barclays dropping 3.6 percent and HSBC falling 1.9 percent. A series of newspaper reports suggested some investment houses faced hundreds of millions of dollars in exposure to asset-backed securities, stoking more uncertainty over the spread of the crisis in the US mortgage sector. Oil shares staged a late slide, leaving BP and Total as the two largest weighted decliners on the FTSEurofirst, in line with declines in Brent crude oil futures. London's FTSE 100 index fell 1.9 percent, while Frankfurt's DAX shed 0.7 percent and Paris' CAC 40 dropped 2.1 perce
